                    <msContents>
                        <summary>A woodblock printed work on astronomy written by Iguchi Jōhan in katakana-majiri and published in 1689. As mentioned in the preface, the background to this work is the adoption of he Jōkyōreki calendar in 1685, replacing the Senmyōreki (宣明暦) calendar which had become at odds with the four seasons in Japan. Much of this work discusses the technical details of calendrical science, but it also covers the prediction of eclipses, the history of calendars in East Asia, and the use of astronomy for the purpose of fortune-telling. </summary>

                        <textLang mainLang="ja" source="IANA">Japanese</textLang>

                        <msItem n="1" xml:id="Japanese_91">

